\end_inset

(80%) In this exercise, we reproduce the “random function generator” (RFG)
 model by 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "friedman2001greedy"

\end_inset

 (the paper is included, see page 19 section 6.1) in R.
 The RFG model generates very complicated data with non-linearity and higher-ord
er interactions.
 The data generated by RFG can be used for testing the performance of many
 fully non-parametric regression-based learning methods such as kernel support
 vector machine (KSVM), gradient boosting, random forests and others.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
The idea is to generate a data frame with 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$N=100$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 observations of simulation data 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$
\backslash
{y_i,
\backslash
textbf{x}_i
\backslash
}_1^N$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 according to
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
y_{i}=f\textbf{({x_{i}})}+\epsilon_{i},
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$
\backslash
epsilon_i$
\end_layout

\end_inset

s are independent generated from the normal distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\epsilon\sim N(0,1)$
\end_inset

.
 In the data frame 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$y$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 takes up the first column, and the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$p=10$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 dimensional vector 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$x$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 takes up the rest columns.
 Hence the data frame will be 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$100
\backslash
times 11$
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 Each row represents one observation.
 The 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$f$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 functions is randomlygenerated as a linear combination of functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\{g_{l}\}_{1}^{20}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
f(x)=\sum_{l=1}^{20}a_{l}g_{l}(\mathbf{z}_{l}),
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\{a_{l}\}_{1}^{20}$
\end_inset

 are randomly generated from a uniform distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{l}\sim\mbox{{U}[-1,1]}$
\end_inset

.
 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
Each 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
$g_l(
\backslash
textbf{z}_l)$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is a function of a randomly selected
\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$p_l$
\end_layout

\end_inset

-size subset (sub-vector) of the 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$p$
\end_layout

\end_inset

-dimensional variable 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$
\backslash
textbf{x}$
\end_layout

\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$p=10$
\end_layout

\end_inset

, and the size of each subset 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$p_l$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is randomly chosen by 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{l}=\min(\lfloor1.5+r\rfloor,p)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$r$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is generated from an exponential distribution 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$r~
\backslash
exp(0.5)$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 with mean 2.
 Each 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$
\backslash
textbf{z}_l$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is a sub-vector of 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$
\backslash
textbf{x}$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 defined as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathbf{z}_{l}=\{\mathbf{x}_{W_{l}(j)}\}_{j=1}^{p_{l}},
\end{align}

\end_inset

 where each 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$W_l$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is an independent permutation of the integers 
\begin_inset Formula $\{1,\dots,p)$
\end_inset

.
 Each function 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{l}(\mathbf{z}_{l})$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$p_l$
\end_layout

\end_inset

-dimensional Gaussian function:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
g_{l}(\mathbf{z_{l})=}\exp\left[-\frac{{1}}{2}(\mathbf{z_{l}-}\mathbf{\mu_{l}})^{T}\mathbf{V}_{l}(\mathbf{z}_{l}-\mu_{l})\right]
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where each of the mean vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\mu_{l}\}_{1}^{20}$
\end_inset

 is randomly generated from the same distribution as that of the input variables
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$
\backslash
textbf{x}$
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$p_l 
\backslash
times p_l$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 covariance matrix 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$
\backslash
textbf{V}_l$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 is also randomly generated by
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathbf{V}_{l}=\mathbf{U}_{l}\mathbf{D}_{l}\mathbf{U}_{l}^{T}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{U}_{l}$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{l}\times p_{l}$
\end_inset

 uniformly distributed random orthonormal matrix and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{D}_{l}=diag\{d_{1l},\dots,d_{p_{l}l}\}$
\end_inset

.
 The variables 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{jl}$
\end_inset

 are randomly generated from a uniform distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{d_{jl}}\sim\mbox{{U}[0.1,2.0]}.$
\end_inset

 We generated 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$x$
\end_layout

\end_inset

 from joint normal distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{x}\sim N(0,\mathbf{I}_{p})$
\end_inset

, with 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

$p=10$
\end_layout

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

